english:
  title: Preface to the New Compilation of the Imperial Physician's Essentials of Medicine
  author: Lee Kyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    What we hold most precious in life is but the body and the breath of life itself. Though death and longevity rest in Heaven's hands, when negligence of health invites disease's assault, and we lack good methods and wondrous remedies to mend what is broken, how many are not snatched away before their time?

    This is why the ancient sages compiled their herbals and formulas—the Materia Medica, the Thousand Gold Remedies, the Dou Men methods, the Holy Sage's cures—to rescue countless lives from calamity. Yet these collections have grown so vast and unwieldy that consulting them proves difficult. When illness lingers and can be delayed, one may seek the physician's counsel or search through the volumes. But when sudden grave illness strikes with urgent peril, who has time to knock upon a doctor's door or rifle through dusty pages?

    Better, then, to gather the essence, to distill what matters most, and keep it close against emergency's hour.

    Our kingdom possessed a compendium of healing arts collected by those versed in such matters. Though brief in form, its efficacy burned bright and saved countless souls. Yet years brought decay, and it lay nearly forgotten.

    Now the esteemed Choi, our Chief Counselor, glimpsed this treasure and grieved its loss. He envisioned its restoration and wider circulation, bringing word to the throne. The King, moved by this devotion to his people's welfare, gave his blessing. The Counselor then divided the work into two volumes, added the most vital remedies, had scribes prepare fair copies, and named it "The Imperial Physician's Essentials of Medicine." By royal mandate, it was sent to the Western Capital to be carved and printed, that it might spread among the people.

    This is the benevolence of a sage kingdom that tends its people as one tends precious children. It is also the noble intent of those who would heal all living things.

    Ah, when goodness appears, I cannot but speak of it. And when asked to write these words, how could I refuse? With respectful bows, I commit these humble observations to paper.

    In the fourth month of the year Byeongsu, this preface is written.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Byeongsu refers to the cyclical year designation in the traditional East Asian calendar; the historical context suggests this is likely 1166 CE or another year in the 12th century.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Western Capital' (西京) refers to Pyeongyang (Pyongyang), which was historically called Seogyeong during the Goryeo period.
